-- 32_llm_functionizer — showcase the LLM-driven Functionizer strategy.
--
-- WHAT THIS TARGETS
-- -----------------
-- This demo classifies HTTP method names (piped on stdin, one per line)
-- as "safe" (read-only / no side effects: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE) or
-- "unsafe" (POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH).
--
-- The classifier is a single pure constraint:
--
--     world_next.classified_line = (world.stdin_line = "GET" ∨ … ?
--                                   world.stdin_line ++ " safe"
--                                 : world.stdin_line ++ " unsafe")
--
-- This is a *String → String* function whose body is string equality +
-- concatenation. The Cranelift JIT REFUSES to compile string equality
-- (it can't reduce a String operand to an i64 in its comparison codegen
-- — see docs/jit-codegen-gaps.md, deferred gap D2). So with the default
-- functionizer this component falls through to a full Z3 solve every
-- call. It is exactly the class of shape the LLM functionizer exists for:
-- something the native JIT can't emit code for, but that an LLM can write
-- a fast, idiomatic Rust function for (`matches!(m, "GET"|"HEAD"|…)`).
--
-- WHY TWO FSMs (the decomposition reason)
-- ---------------------------------------
-- The runtime's `decompose_simplified` unions any two outputs touched by
-- the same assertion. Putting the classifier in the SAME body as the
-- printer would merge `is_safe` with `effects` (the Println references
-- it), and `Plan::from_program` rejects any component containing a Seq
-- step. So `classifier` does NOTHING but compute the classified string
-- and publish it through world. The LLM-targeted output —
-- `world_next.classified_line` — is referenced by no other assertion in
-- the classifier's body, so it decomposes into its own single-Scalar-
-- step component, exactly the shape `Plan::from_program` accepts.
--
-- `printer` reads `world.classified_line` (written by `classifier` in
-- the same tick — writer-first scheduling on the disjoint write field)
-- and just emits the right Println. It owns the banner, the sequencing,
-- and the Exit(0). Neither FSM references the classifier's logic — only
-- the published string crosses the wire between them.
--
-- HOW THE LLM PATH WORKS (and its validation gate)
-- ------------------------------------------------
-- With `--functionizer llm` AND a valid `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, the runtime
-- (functionize/llm.rs) for the `classifier` FSM's classified_line
-- component:
--   1. Samples input→output pairs by solving this constraint with Z3 —
--      Z3 is the ground-truth ORACLE (e.g. ("GET", "GET safe"),
--      ("POST", "POST unsafe"), ("zzz", "zzz unsafe"), …).
--   2. Splits them into a training set (shown to the LLM in the prompt)
--      and a HELD-OUT validation set (never shown).
--   3. Asks the LLM to write `fn compute(world_stdin_line: &str) ->
--      String`, compiles it with `rustc` into a cdylib, and `dlopen`s it.
--   4. Accepts the function ONLY if it reproduces Z3 on EVERY held-out
--      pair. Any miss → reject → fall through to Z3. This validation gate
--      is the sole guard against a hallucinated function: wrong logic
--      can't pass because Z3 disagrees with it on the held-out set.
--
-- HONEST COST / QUALITY TRADE-OFF
-- -------------------------------
-- The LLM path is SLOW (a network round-trip + an out-of-process `rustc`
-- compile), EXPENSIVE (one API call per cache miss — the compiled
-- function is cached per claim, so it's one call per program shape, not
-- per tick), and UNCERTAIN (the model can hallucinate; that's why every
-- candidate is validated against Z3 and rejected on any mismatch). It is
-- worth paying ONLY when no cheaper functionizer (Cranelift) can compile
-- the shape — string manipulation, regex-like classification, and other
-- domain transforms the arithmetic JIT has no codegen for.
--
-- NO-API-KEY BEHAVIOR (the CI path)
-- ---------------------------------
-- Without a key the LLM generator declines (no network call), `compile`
-- returns None, and the runtime falls through to its normal path — the
-- Cranelift JIT for the arithmetic components and a Z3 solve for the
-- string classifier. The program runs identically and exits 0; only the
-- *how* of the classifier changes. Selecting `--functionizer llm` with
-- no key prints a clear "LLM functionizer requires ANTHROPIC_API_KEY,
-- skipping" message and uses the fallback. This file's CI row exercises
-- exactly that fallback path.
--
-- Run it:
--   printf 'GET\nPOST\nPUT\nHEAD\nDELETE\nOPTIONS\nTRACE\nPATCH\n\n' \
--     | evident effect-run examples/test_32_llm_functionizer.ev
--   # compile the classifier via the LLM (needs a key + rustc on PATH):
--   ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=… evident effect-run --functionizer llm \
--     examples/test_32_llm_functionizer.ev   < methods.txt

import "stdlib/runtime.ev"

-- StdinSource auto-installs on this World shape: it writes one line per
-- Enter (or piped newline) to `stdin_line` and bumps `stdin_seq`.
-- `classified_line` is written by the `classifier` FSM below — the
-- multi-writer disjoint check accepts this because each field has
-- exactly one writer (StdinSource owns stdin_*, classifier owns
-- classified_*).
type World
    stdin_line ∈ String
    stdin_seq  ∈ Int
    classified_line ∈ String

-- Classifier is intentionally stateless beyond the FSM scaffolding —
-- one variant suffices. The first variant must be nullary (seed tick 0).
enum CState = Active

-- ⭐ THE LLM-TARGETED FSM ⭐
--
-- This FSM exists ONLY so the classifier can live in a body where
-- nothing else references `classified_line`. With this isolation,
-- `decompose_simplified` carves `{world.classified_line}` out as its own
-- single-output component; `Plan::from_program` sees ONE Scalar step
-- (String → String) and accepts it; the LLM gets prompted, the
-- candidate is validated against held-out Z3 samples, and on a match
-- the runtime mounts the cdylib in place of the slow solve.
fsm classifier(world, world_next ∈ World, state ∈ CState)
    -- Pure String → String: append " safe" iff the line is one of the
    -- four safe HTTP methods (GET / HEAD / OPTIONS / TRACE), otherwise
    -- " unsafe". The boundary case of "" → " unsafe" is harmless: the
    -- printer never emits the empty-line classification (it gates on
    -- `world.stdin_line ≠ ""`).
    world_next.classified_line = (world.stdin_line = "GET" ∨ world.stdin_line = "HEAD"
                                  ∨ world.stdin_line = "OPTIONS" ∨ world.stdin_line = "TRACE"
                                  ? world.stdin_line ++ " safe"
                                  : world.stdin_line ++ " unsafe")

    state_next = Active
    effects = ⟨⟩

-- Start: nullary first variant so the runtime can seed tick 0.
-- Listening(Int): carries the last-printed line's seq.
enum PState = PStart | PListening(Int) | PDone

-- The printer reads `world.classified_line` (written by `classifier`
-- earlier in the same tick — writer-first scheduling) and emits it.
-- It owns the banner, the per-line print, and the graceful Exit on
-- end-of-input. None of its body references the classifier's logic,
-- only the published `classified_line` string.
fsm printer(world ∈ World, state ∈ PState)
    last_seq ∈ Int
    last_seq = match state
        PStart        ⇒ 0
        PListening(s) ⇒ s
        PDone         ⇒ 0

    -- A new line arrived iff the source bumped the seq past what we last printed.
    fresh ∈ Bool = (world.stdin_seq > last_seq)

    -- A blank line (or piped trailing newline) is the end-of-input sentinel.
    at_end ∈ Bool = (fresh ∧ world.stdin_line = "")
    has_method ∈ Bool = (fresh ∧ world.stdin_line ≠ "")

    state_next = match state
        PStart        ⇒ PListening(0)
        PListening(_) ⇒ (at_end ? PDone : PListening(world.stdin_seq))
        PDone         ⇒ PDone

    effects = match state
        PStart        ⇒ ⟨Println("HTTP method safety classifier — LLM functionizer demo"),
                        Println("(no ANTHROPIC_API_KEY → Z3 solves the string classifier;"),
                        Println(" set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY + --functionizer llm to compile it via the LLM)")⟩
        PListening(_) ⇒ (at_end ? ⟨Println("done — classified every method"), Exit(0)⟩
                         : (has_method ? ⟨Println(world.classified_line)⟩
                                       : ⟨⟩))
        PDone         ⇒ ⟨⟩

-- ── Static tests ─────────────────────────────────────────────

-- A safe method classifies as " safe" …
claim sat_classifier_get_is_safe
    world ∈ World
    world_next ∈ World
    state ∈ CState
    state_next ∈ CState
    last_results ∈ Seq(Result)
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect)
    world.stdin_line = "GET"
    world.stdin_seq = 1
    state = Active
    classifier
    world_next.classified_line = "GET safe"

-- An unsafe method classifies as " unsafe" …
claim sat_classifier_post_is_unsafe
    world ∈ World
    world_next ∈ World
    state ∈ CState
    state_next ∈ CState
    last_results ∈ Seq(Result)
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect)
    world.stdin_line = "POST"
    world.stdin_seq = 1
    state = Active
    classifier
    world_next.classified_line = "POST unsafe"

-- TRACE is one of the four safe methods (not just GET) — guards against a
-- classifier that only recognizes the first listed method.
claim sat_classifier_trace_is_safe
    world ∈ World
    world_next ∈ World
    state ∈ CState
    state_next ∈ CState
    last_results ∈ Seq(Result)
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect)
    world.stdin_line = "TRACE"
    world.stdin_seq = 1
    state = Active
    classifier
    world_next.classified_line = "TRACE safe"

-- The printer prints the classified line when a fresh method arrived.
claim sat_printer_emits_classified
    world ∈ World
    state ∈ PState
    state_next ∈ PState
    last_results ∈ Seq(Result)
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect)
    world.stdin_line = "GET"
    world.stdin_seq = 1
    world.classified_line = "GET safe"
    state = PListening(0)
    printer
    effects = ⟨Println("GET safe")⟩

-- A blank line ends input: transition to PDone and emit Exit(0).
claim sat_printer_blank_line_exits
    world ∈ World
    state ∈ PState
    state_next ∈ PState
    last_results ∈ Seq(Result)
    effects ∈ Seq(Effect)
    world.stdin_line = ""
    world.stdin_seq = 9
    world.classified_line = " unsafe"
    state = PListening(3)
    printer
    state_next = PDone
